.TH "gpiochip_add_pin_range" 9 "gpiochip_add_pin_range" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
gpiochip_add_pin_range \- add a range for GPIO <-> pin mapping
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" gpiochip_add_pin_range
.BI "(struct gpio_chip *gc "  ","
.BI "const char *pinctl_name "  ","
.BI "unsigned int gpio_offset "  ","
.BI "unsigned int pin_offset "  ","
.BI "unsigned int npins "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "gc" 12
the gpiochip to add the range for
.IP "pinctl_name" 12
the \fBdev_name\fP of the pin controller to map to
.IP "gpio_offset" 12
the start offset in the current gpio_chip number space
.IP "pin_offset" 12
the start offset in the pin controller number space
.IP "npins" 12
the number of pins from the offset of each pin space (GPIO and
pin controller) to accumulate in this range
.SH "RETURN"
0 on success, or a negative error-code on failure.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Calling this function directly from a DeviceTree-supported
pinctrl driver is DEPRECATED. Please see Section 2.1 of
Documentation/devicetree/bindings/gpio/gpio.txt on how to
bind pinctrl and gpio drivers via the "gpio-ranges" property.
